<article>
    <h1>Beijing vows to re&#xAD;tal&#xAD;i&#xAD;ate against US di&#xAD;plo&#xAD;mats, in&#xAD;clud&#xAD;ing those in HK</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20200912/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-09-12"><time>2020-09-12</time></a>
        - <span>WORLD</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>•</p>
    <p>Beijing said it will take un­spec­i­fied re­tal­ia­tory mea­sures against US di­plo­mats in China, in­clud­ing those work­ing in Hong Kong, fol­low­ing ear­lier moves by the Trump ad­min­is­tra­tion to limit the ways Chi­nese di­plo­mats can op­er­ate on United States soil.</p>
    <p>China no­ti­fied the US of the “re­cip­ro­cal” mea­sures be­ing taken against its di­plo­mats, For­eign Min­istry spokesman Zhao Li­jian said in a state­ment yes­ter­day evening, with­out giv­ing any de­tails.</p>
    <p>“The US prac­tice has se­verely vi­o­lated in­ter­na­tional law and ba­sic norms gov­ern­ing in­ter­na­tional re­la­tions and dis­rupted China-US re­la­tions and nor­mal ex­changes be­tween the two sides,” Mr Zhao said.</p>
    <p>US Sec­re­tary of State Mike Pom­peo ear­lier this month un­veiled new rules on Chi­nese di­plo­mats that are de­signed to match those al­ready im­posed on Amer­i­can di­plo­mats in China.</p>
    <p>Un­der those up­dated rules, se­nior Chi­nese di­plo­mats must seek ap­proval to visit univer­sity cam­puses or meet lo­cal gov­ern­ment of­fi­cials, the State De­part­ment said in a pre­vi­ous state­ment.</p>
    <p>Un­like some US sanc­tions that have had a sig­nif­i­cant im­pact on Chi­nese tech­nol­ogy and fi­nan­cial firms, as well as some of­fi­cials, Chi­nese sanc­tions some­times ap­pear to mean lit­tle.</p>
    <p>None of the dozen Amer­i­can in­di­vid­u­als sanc­tioned since July has re­ceived no­tice of what the penal­ties would en­tail, in­clud­ing Sen­a­tors Marco Ru­bio of Florida and Ted Cruz of Texas.</p>
    <p>Beijing’s pledged sanc­tions against US firms, in­clud­ing Lock­heed Martin, which sells weapon sys­tems to Tai­wan in de­fi­ance of</p>
    <p>China, have also had lit­tle im­pact, ac­cord­ing to some in­dus­try an­a­lysts.</p>
    <p>The new devel­op­ments come as the two su­per­pow­ers en­gage in a broader tit-for-tat bat­tle on ev­ery­thing from trade and tech­nol­ogy to me­dia ac­cred­i­ta­tion and di­plo­matic pro­to­cols.</p>
    <p>The ad­min­is­tra­tion of Pres­i­dent Don­ald Trump has taken a range of mea­sures, from hit­ting out at Chi­nese tech­nol­ogy firms to slap­ping sanc­tions on of­fi­cials in Hong Kong and im­pos­ing stricter re­quire­ments on Chi­nese jour­nal­ists in the US.</p>
    <p>China has also ex­pelled US jour­nal­ists.</p>
    <p>In July, the State De­part­ment also or­dered the Chi­nese con­sulate in Hous­ton closed “to pro­tect Amer­i­can in­tel­lec­tual prop­erty and Amer­i­cans’ pri­vate in­for­ma­tion”, prompt­ing China to shut the US con­sulate in Chengdu days later.</p>


</article>

